import pandas as pd

import sys
import warnings
if not sys.warnoptions:
    warnings.simplefilter("ignore")
The following report outlines an analysis of the Jumpman23 project during October 2014, its first month in New York. The report covers the following sections:¶
  1. Notes on data integrity
  2. Summary statistics
  3. Number of deliveries per week, day and hour
  4. Deliveries by location
  5. Delivery durations
  6. Jumpmen analysis
  7. Customer retention
  8. Conclusion

1. Notes on data integrity¶

  • The following features have missing values:
    • "how_long_it_took_to_order": 2945 of 5938 values are missing. Note: because of the many missing values, the time it took to order has not been considered in section 5: Delivery duration.
    • "when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_pickup": 550 values are missing
    • "when_the_Jumpman_left_pickup": 550 values are missing
    • "place_category": 883 values are missing (replaced them with "Unknown")
    • "item_name", "item_quantity", "item_category_name": 1230 values are missing (replaced them with "Unknown")
  • The feature "when_the_delivery_started" was not always recorded at the correct time. In 501 cases "when_the_delivery_started" was recorded later than "when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_pickup". For the purpose of this report, the delivery time calculations of the affected cases have been ignored. However, it might be that "when_the_delivery_started" was recorded late in other cases as well. Therefore, this report might have underestimated the median delivery time.

2. Summary statistics¶

In [3]:
# ---------- Load and prepare data ---------- #
data = pd.read_csv('analyze_me.csv')
# concatenate similar categories:
def revise_place_category(x):
    if x in ['Burger', 'American']:
        x = 'American/Burger'
    if x in ['Italian', 'Pizza']:
        x = 'Italian/Pizza'
    if x in ['Japanese', 'Sushi']:
        x = 'Japanese/Sushi'
    if x in ['Bakery', 'Dessert']:
        x = 'Bakery/Dessert'
    return x
# handle missing data:
data.place_category = data.place_category.fillna('Unknown')
data.item_name = data.item_name.fillna('Unknown')
data.item_category_name = data.item_category_name.fillna('Unknown')
data.item_quantity = data.item_quantity.fillna(1) # <- assume item quantity = 1 if unknown
# convert time data to datetime format:
data.place_category = data.place_category.apply(revise_place_category)
data.when_the_delivery_started = pd.to_datetime(data.when_the_delivery_started)
data.when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_pickup = pd.to_datetime(data.when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_pickup)
data.when_the_Jumpman_left_pickup = pd.to_datetime(data.when_the_Jumpman_left_pickup)
data.when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_dropoff = pd.to_datetime(data.when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_dropoff)
# add a column for the time it took to order in minutes:
data['how_long_it_took_to_order_min'] = data.how_long_it_took_to_order.\
    apply(lambda x: pd.Timestamp(x).minute + 1/60 * pd.Timestamp(x).second)
# add column with day of week (0: Monday, 6: Sunday) 
data['weekday'] = data.when_the_delivery_started.apply(lambda x: x.weekday())
# add columns with amount of time it took for different tasks (and convert time to hours): 
# (first remove "when_the_delivery_started" if time after "when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_pickup")
data['time_JM_to_pickup'] = data.when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_pickup - data.when_the_delivery_started
recorded_late_when_delivery_started = data['time_JM_to_pickup'].apply(lambda x: x.days) < 0 
data['time_JM_to_pickup'][recorded_late_when_delivery_started] = pd.NaT
data['time_JM_to_pickup'] = data['time_JM_to_pickup'].apply(lambda x: pd.NaT if x.days < 0 else x)
data['time_JM_to_pickup'] = data['time_JM_to_pickup'].apply(lambda x: x.seconds/3600)
data['time_JM_wait'] = data.when_the_Jumpman_left_pickup - data.when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_pickup
data['time_JM_wait'] = data['time_JM_wait'].apply(lambda x: x.seconds/3600)
data['time_JM_to_dropoff'] = data.when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_dropoff - data.when_the_Jumpman_left_pickup
data['time_JM_to_dropoff'] = data['time_JM_to_dropoff'].apply(lambda x: x.seconds/3600)
data['time_delivery'] = data.when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_dropoff - data.when_the_delivery_started
data['time_delivery'][recorded_late_when_delivery_started] = pd.NaT
data['time_delivery'] = data['time_delivery'].apply(lambda x: x.seconds/3600)
# create new data frame "data_ud" containing only unique delivery ids (info on items lost)
data_ud = data
deliver_ids_appeared = []
deliver_id_first_time = []
for id_ in data['delivery_id']:
    if id_ in deliver_ids_appeared:
        deliver_id_first_time.append(False)
    else:
        deliver_id_first_time.append(True)
        deliver_ids_appeared.append(id_)
data_ud['deliver_id_first_time'] = deliver_id_first_time
data_ud = data_ud[data_ud['deliver_id_first_time']]

# ---------- Summary statistics ---------- #
n_deliveries = data_ud.shape[0]
first_date = data_ud.when_the_delivery_started.min()
last_date = data_ud.when_the_delivery_started.max()
n_days = last_date.day - first_date.day + 1
n_items = data.item_quantity.sum()
n_customers = data_ud.customer_id.unique().shape[0]
n_jumpmen = data_ud.jumpman_id.unique().shape[0]
avg_delivery_time = int(np.round(data_ud.time_delivery.mean() * 60))
avg_order_place_time = int(data['how_long_it_took_to_order_min'].mean())

print('Market data from ' + first_date.month_name() + ' ' + str(first_date.day) + ' to ' +\
      last_date.month_name() + ' ' + str(last_date.day) + ', ' + str(last_date.year) + 
      ' (in total ' + str(n_days) + (' days') + str(')\n'))
print('Total number of deliveries: ' + str(n_deliveries) + ' (' + str(np.round(n_deliveries / n_days)) + 
      ' per day)\n')
print('Total number of delivered items: ' + str(int(n_items)) + '\n')
print(str('Total number of customers: ') + str(n_customers) + '\n')
print(str('Total number of Jumpmen involved: ') + str(n_jumpmen) + '\n')
print('Average delivery time: ' + str(avg_delivery_time) + ' minutes\n')
print('Average time it took to place order: ' +str(avg_order_place_time) + ' minutes')

# Activity over month
deliveries_per_day = data_ud.when_the_delivery_started.apply(lambda x: x.day).value_counts().sort_index()
deliveries_per_week = deliveries_per_day.rolling(7).sum()[6:]

# Activity per weekday:
deliveries_per_weekday = data_ud.weekday.value_counts().sort_index()
unique_days = data_ud.when_the_delivery_started.dropna().apply(lambda x: x.date()).unique()
from collections import defaultdict
d = defaultdict(int)
for day in unique_days:
    d[day.weekday()] += 1
deliveries_per_weekday = list(data_ud.when_the_delivery_started.apply(lambda x: x.weekday()).\
                              value_counts().sort_index())
# count number of deliveries for each weekday (some appear 4 times, others 5 times)
deliveries_per_weekday_norm = []
for i, deliveries in enumerate(deliveries_per_weekday):
    deliveries_per_weekday_norm.append(deliveries/d[i])

fig, [ax1, ax2] = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2)

ax2.set_ylabel('Number of deliveries')
ax2.set_title('Average number of deliveries per weekday')
plt.show()
  • The total number of deliveries per week increased from around 1150 on October 7th to more than 1300 on October 30th
  • On Sundays we have significantly more activity than during the week (~240 deliveries on an average Sunday vs ~160 deliveries on an average weekday)

# ---------- Activity over day ---------- #
n_weekend_days = d[5] + d[6]
n_week_days = n_days - n_weekend_days
deliveries_per_hour = data_ud.when_the_delivery_started.apply(lambda x: x.hour).value_counts()
deliveries_per_hour /= n_days

# take a separate look at weekdays vs weekends:
data_weekend = data_ud[(data_ud.weekday == 5) | (data_ud.weekday == 6)]
deliveries_per_hour_weekend = data_weekend.when_the_delivery_started.apply(lambda x: x.hour).value_counts()
deliveries_per_hour_weekend /= n_weekend_days
data_weekdays = data_ud[(data_ud.weekday != 5) & (data_ud.weekday != 6)]
deliveries_per_hour_weekdays = data_weekdays.when_the_delivery_started.apply(lambda x: x.hour).value_counts()
deliveries_per_hour_weekdays /= n_week_days

# Fill in 0's for the hours without any deliveries:
for i in range(24):
    if i not in deliveries_per_hour.index:
        deliveries_per_hour[i] = 0
    if i not in deliveries_per_hour_weekend.index:
        deliveries_per_hour_weekend[i] = 0
    if i not in deliveries_per_hour_weekdays.index:
        deliveries_per_hour_weekdays[i] = 0
deliveries_per_hour = deliveries_per_hour.sort_index()
deliveries_per_hour_weekend = deliveries_per_hour_weekend.sort_index()
deliveries_per_hour_weekdays = deliveries_per_hour_weekdays.sort_index()
am = [str(i) + 'am' for i in range(1, 13)]
pm = [str(i) + 'pm' for i in range(1, 13)]
hour_labels = [am[-1]] + am[:-1] + [pm[-1]] + pm[:-1]

x = list(deliveries_per_hour.index)
y_all = list(deliveries_per_hour.values)
y_weekend = list(deliveries_per_hour_weekend.values)
y_weekdays = list(deliveries_per_hour_weekdays.values)

plt2.rcParams.update({'figure.figsize': [8.5, 4.5], 'font.size': 14})
plt2.plot(y_all, alpha=1, c='black', linewidth=2.5)
plt2.plot(y_weekend, alpha=0.6, c='red')
plt2.plot(y_weekdays, alpha=0.6, c='blue')
plt2.xticks(x, hour_labels, rotation='45', fontsize=10)#, minor=True)
plt2.ylabel('Number of deliveries')
plt2.title('Daily activity: Average number of deliveries per hour')
plt.legend(['all days', 'on weekends', 'on weekdays'])
plt2.show()
  • We see that the number of deliveries has a peak around lunchtime (Noon-1pm) on weekdays and another higher peak around dinner time (6pm to 8pm)
  • On weekends there is no significant drop in orders after lunch time, the peak around dinner time remains

# Add column in data set for area (Manhattan North, Manhattan South, Brooklyn)
pntA = (-73.927, 40.75)
pntB = (-73.97, 40.75)
pntC = (-73.97, 40.708)
pntD = (-74.004, 40.708)
pickup_lat = data_ud.pickup_lat
pickup_lon = data_ud.pickup_lon
pickup_area = []
for lat, lon in zip(pickup_lat, pickup_lon):
    if lat >= pntA[1]:
        if lon <= pntA[0]:
            pickup_area.append('Manhattan North')
        else:
            pickup_area.append('Brooklyn')
    elif lat >= pntC[1]:
        if lon <= pntC[0]:
            pickup_area.append('Manhattan South')
        else:
            pickup_area.append('Brooklyn')
    else:
        if lon <= pntD[0]:
            pickup_area.append('Manhattan South')
        else:
            pickup_area.append('Brooklyn')
data_ud['pickup_area'] = pickup_area

5. Delivery duration¶

Let's take a look at the delivery duration. The total delivery duration is the sum of the following 3 components:

  • Time until Jumpan arrived ad Pickup
  • Time Jumpman waited at Pickup
  • Time Jumpan took to deliver to drop-off

Note: The time it took to place an order has not been taken into account in this analysis due to too many missing values. It took on average 7 minutes to place an order

In [14]:
# ---------- Plot delivery times and components ---------- #
# remove rows with delivery times > 3hrs (outliers, in total there are 5)
data_dt = data_ud[data_ud['time_delivery'] < 3]
JM_to_pickup_min = data_dt['time_JM_to_pickup'].dropna() * 60

JM_to_dropoff_min = data_dt['time_JM_to_dropoff'].dropna() * 60

fig.show()

The following things stand out:

  • In rare cases the Jumpman needs more than 30 minutes to arrive at the pickup location. This indicates limited Jumpmen availability (might depend on time and location)
  • The time Jumpen wait at the pickup location is usually less than 30 minutes
  • With a median of 12 min delivery time, most orders seem to come from drop-off locations that are relatively close to the pickup location

The boxplots above show the distribution of the different delivery time components by area. We notice an interesting difference between Brooklyn and the two areas in Manhattan: While the wait time and time for the Jumpman to drop-off tend to be relatively short in Brooklyn, the time a Jumpan takes to get to the pickup location is often the longest in Brooklyn. This indicates that Brooklyn tends to be at limited capacity and could use more Jumpmen.

Delivery times by day time¶

Let's take a look how the median delivery time changes during an average day

In [16]:
# ---------- Plot delivery time by time of day ---------- #
time_JM_to_pickup_per_hour = []
JM_wait_per_hour = []
JM_to_dropoff_per_hour = []
delivery_total_per_hour = []
for h in np.arange(9, 24):
    time_JM_to_pickup_per_hour.append(np.median(data_dt[data_dt.when_the_delivery_started.\
            apply(lambda x: x.hour) == h]['time_JM_to_pickup'].dropna()) * 60)
    JM_wait_per_hour.append(np.median(data_dt[data_dt.when_the_delivery_started.\
            apply(lambda x: x.hour) == h]['time_JM_wait'].dropna()) * 60)
    JM_to_dropoff_per_hour.append(np.median(data_dt[data_dt.when_the_delivery_started.\
            apply(lambda x: x.hour) == h]['time_JM_to_dropoff'].dropna()) * 60)
    delivery_total_per_hour.append(np.median(data_dt[data_dt.when_the_delivery_started.\
            apply(lambda x: x.hour) == h]['time_delivery'].dropna()) * 60)
plt2.rcParams.update({'figure.figsize': [6, 3], 'font.size': 10})
plt2.plot(time_JM_to_pickup_per_hour, alpha=0.8, c='red', linewidth=2)
plt2.plot(JM_wait_per_hour, alpha=0.8, c='seagreen', linewidth=2)
plt2.plot(JM_to_dropoff_per_hour, alpha=0.8, c='royalblue', linewidth=2)
plt2.plot(delivery_total_per_hour, alpha=0.8, c='black', linewidth=2)
plt2.xticks(list(np.arange(0, 15)), hour_labels[9:], rotation='45', fontsize=10)
plt2.ylabel('minutes')
plt2.ylim([0, 55])
plt2.title('Median delivery time per time of the day')
plt.legend(['Time Jumpman to pickup', 'Wait time at pickup', 'Time Jumpman to dropoff', \
           'Total delivery time'], bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
plt2.show()

While the median waiting time and delivery time remain approximately constant during the day, we can see that the time a Jumpman needs to arrive at the pickup location peeks at the busiest time (around dinner time). This indicates that there might be the need for more Jumpmen around these hours.

7. Customer retention¶

Let's take a look at customer retention. Let's define a returning customer as a customer that used Jumpman23 at least twice during the one month period. For this purpose we don't consider customers that ordered for the first time on any of the last seven days of the period since they might become returning customers within an additional few days.

In [20]:
# ---------- Analyze customer retention ---------- #
data_cr = data_ud[data_ud['when_the_delivery_started'].apply(lambda x: x.day) <= n_days - 7]
data_cr.groupby('customer_id').agg('count')
returning_costumers = pd.DataFrame(data_ud['customer_id'].value_counts() > 1)
return_customer = []
for id_ in data_cr['customer_id']:
    if returning_costumers.loc[id_].bool():
        return_customer.append(1)
    else:
        return_customer.append(0)
data_cr['return_customer'] = return_customer
# Remove rows with customers that already appeared before:
customer_ids_appeared = []
customer_first_time = []
for id_ in data_cr['customer_id']:
    if id_ in customer_ids_appeared:
        customer_first_time.append(False)
    else:
        customer_first_time.append(True)
        customer_ids_appeared.append(id_)
data_cr['customer_first_time'] = customer_first_time
data_cr = data_cr[data_cr['customer_first_time']]
# Annotate bars with percentage:
yes = int(np.round(100 * data_cr['return_customer'].sum() / data_cr['return_customer'].shape[0]))
no = 100 - yes
labels = [str(no) + '%', str(yes) + '%']
# Create plot:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
plt.rcParams.update({'figure.figsize': [4.5, 2.5], 'font.size': 12})
ax.barh(['no', 'yes'], data_cr['return_customer'].value_counts(), color=['orange', 'royalblue'])
ax.set_xlabel('Total number of customers')
ax.set_title('Did customers return?')
rects = ax.patches
for rect, label in zip(rects, labels):
    x_value = rect.get_width()
    y_value = rect.get_y() + rect.get_height() / 2
    ax.text(x_value - 200, y_value, label, color='white', fontsize=15, style='italic', weight='bold')#,
plt.show()

We see that only 36% of customers returned after using Jumpman23 for the first time. This is certainly an area with potential for improvement. Let's see if we can find indicators of what factors lead to customer retention.

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5, 2))

Another idea is that the delivery time has an influence on customers loyalty. If deliveries take longer on average, it might upset the customer and he/she might not return. The median delivery time is very similar between returning and non-returning customers. Non-returning customers experienced unusually long waiting times slightly more often than returning ones.

Most frequent places categories and returning customers by places category¶

In [23]:
# ---------- Analyze categories of most popular places ---------- #
data_pc = data_ud[data_ud.place_category != 'Unknown'] # <- don't consider 'Unknown' a category
data_cr_pc = data_cr[data_cr.place_category != 'Unknown']
total_n = data_pc.place_category.value_counts().sum()
top_15_place_cat = data_pc.place_category.value_counts()[:17]
top_15_place_cat = top_15_place_cat[::-1] / (total_n / 100)
top_15_categories = list(data_cr_pc.place_category.value_counts().iloc[:17].index)
data_cr_top15 = data_cr_pc[data_cr_pc.place_category.isin(top_15_categories)]
ct_return_cat = pd.crosstab(data_cr_top15.place_category, data_cr_top15.return_customer, \
                            normalize='index').sort_values(by=0, ascending=False)

fig.tight_layout()

ax2.set_ylabel('', fontsize=14)

We can see the American, Japanese and Italian food is especially popular in New York. The customer retention shows little variance among these popular categories. Customers who ordered from a vegetarian place when they used the service for the first time are the only ones that returned in more than 50% of the cases. However, vegetarian places only represent a small fraction (~1.5%) of all orders.

8. Conclusion¶

Overall, things are going well in New York. In one month we were able to increase the number of deliveries by almost 20% (from ~1150 to ~1350 deliveries per week). Currently, however, almost all the action occurs in Manhattan. There is much potential for more business in Brooklyn and possibly in Queens and the Bronx as well. To increase business we need to make sure to not only attract more customers but also to attract more Jumpmen, as Jumpmen travel times to pickup locations indicate limited capacity at certain times and locations. We should also strongly focus on our relationships with merchants that sell American, Japanese and Italian food, as these places are especially popular in New York.
